body:
# Redis Pub/Sub

Redis pub/sub enables real-time messaging between publishers and subscribers through named channels. Publishers send messages to channels. Subscribers listen on channels and receive messages instantly. This is the foundation for cache invalidation (see [[redis/caching#invalidation]]), real-time notifications, and inter-service communication. Connect using the configuration in [[redis#connection]].

## Publish and Subscribe

```javascript
import Redis from "ioredis";

// Subscriber needs a dedicated connection
const sub = new Redis(process.env.REDIS_URL);
const pub = new Redis(process.env.REDIS_URL);

// Subscribe to a channel
await sub.subscribe("notifications", "alerts");

sub.on("message", (channel, message) => {
  console.log(`[${channel}] ${message}`);
});

// Publish to a channel (returns number of subscribers who received it)
const subscriberCount = await pub.publish("notifications", JSON.stringify({
  type: "order",
  orderId: "ORD-1234",
  status: "shipped",
}));
console.log(`Delivered to ${subscriberCount} subscribers`);
```

## Pattern Matching

Subscribe to channels matching a glob pattern:

```javascript
// Subscribe to all channels starting with "user:"
await sub.psubscribe("user:*");

// Subscribe to all event channels
await sub.psubscribe("events.*");

sub.on("pmessage", (pattern, channel, message) => {
  console.log(`Pattern: ${pattern}, Channel: ${channel}, Message: ${message}`);
});

// Publish to specific channels — pattern subscribers receive them
await pub.publish("user:1001:login", "session-started");
await pub.publish("user:1002:logout", "session-ended");
await pub.publish("events.order.created", JSON.stringify({ id: "ORD-5678" }));
```

Supported glob patterns:
- `*` — matches any sequence of characters
- `?` — matches exactly one character
- `[abc]` — matches one of the enclosed characters

## Reliability Considerations

Redis pub/sub is **fire-and-forget**:

- Messages are delivered only to **currently connected** subscribers
- If a subscriber disconnects and reconnects, it **misses all messages** sent during the gap
- There is **no message persistence** or replay capability
- There is **no acknowledgment** — the publisher does not know if subscribers processed the message

For durable, replayable messaging with consumer groups and acknowledgment, use [[redis/streams]] instead.

| Feature | Pub/Sub | Streams |
|---------|---------|----------|
| Persistence | No | Yes (append-only log) |
| Replay | No | Yes (read from any ID) |
| Consumer groups | No | Yes |
| Acknowledgment | No | Yes (XACK) |
| Ordering | Delivery order | Stream ID order |
| Best for | Real-time broadcast | Durable event processing |

## Use Cases

- **Cache invalidation** — broadcast invalidation events across application instances. See [[redis/caching#invalidation]].
- **Real-time notifications** — push updates to connected clients (WebSocket bridges).
- **Inter-service communication** — lightweight event bus between microservices.
- **Configuration updates** — propagate config changes across a fleet of workers.
- **Chat and presence** — channel-based messaging for chat applications.

## Connection Management

```javascript
// ioredis requires a dedicated connection for subscriptions
// A subscriber connection CANNOT issue non-pub/sub commands
const sub = new Redis(process.env.REDIS_URL);  // dedicated subscriber
const pub = new Redis(process.env.REDIS_URL);  // for publishing + general commands

// Unsubscribe from specific channels
await sub.unsubscribe("notifications");

// Unsubscribe from all channels
await sub.unsubscribe();

// Check active channels and subscriber counts
const channels = await pub.pubsub("CHANNELS", "*");
const count = await pub.pubsub("NUMSUB", "notifications");
```
